<strong>William Henry</strong> has ruled that CNN lacked evidence that Youn=
g did anything illegal, greenlighting a trial to begin on January 6 and all=
owing Young to pursue punitive damages.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As trial day ap=
proaches, tensions have escalated. Young=E2=80=99s legal team, led by <stro=
ng>Velvel Freedman</strong>, deposed CNN anchor <strong>Jake Tapper</strong=
> on his salary and his views of Trump. Freedman also raised
the $787 million penalty Fox News paid Dominion to settle the voting machin=
e vendor=E2=80=99s defamation case. Seemingly intent on drawing parallels b=
etween the Dominion case and Young=E2=80=99s, Freedman asked Tapper whether=
 such a punishment would be enough to deter CNN from further defamatory con=
duct.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At a court hearing I observed last week, C=
NN=E2=80=99s attorney <strong>Charles Tobin</strong> blasted the deposition=
 as
a =E2=80=9Ctotal freak show,=E2=80=9D adding, =E2=80=9CThis was very clearl=
y an ambush deposition =E2=80=A6 designed to get Mr. Tapper to say somethin=
g in a nice tight colloquy that they could play to a jury.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">CNN has now moved to exclude mentions of Trump, Fox News=
, or the Dominion settlement at trial, arguing these subjects could inflame=
 sensitivities among jurors in Florida=E2=80=99s deep-red Bay County. On Mo=
nday, Freedman filed an
opposition brief, contending there=E2=80=99s no exclusion for political top=
ics, arguing that Tapper=E2=80=99s discussion of the Dominion settlement go=
es to what the network=E2=80=99s marquee anchor understood about journalist=
ic standards=E2=80=94and implying that Young will ask the jury for <em>more=
</em> than $787 million in damages. He writes: =E2=80=9CIf CNN recognized t=
he significance of the Dominion settlement as a cautionary tale yet still c=
hose to defame Young, that fact demonstrates the insufficiency of prior mon=
etary amounts
in deterring CNN=E2=80=99s misconduct.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhi=
le, CNN=E2=80=99s trial strategy is coming into focus. The network plans to=
 call witnesses like <strong>Ralf Otto</strong>, who works with Civil Fleet=
, a German N.G.O. that paid Young to evacuate six Afghans. Otto will testif=
y that Young collected money in advance, yet only managed to evacuate three=
 of the six, prompting Civil Fleet to hire a different contractor for a
fraction of Young=E2=80=99s price. CNN will also present testimony from <st=
rong>George McMillan</strong>, a geopolitical analyst who met Young and cam=
e away feeling =E2=80=9Che could be a fraud.=E2=80=9D The goal is clear: to=
 convince the jury that CNN=E2=80=99s description of Young as exploitative =
wasn=E2=80=99t defamatory, but rather an accurate reflection of his reputat=
ion.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">These witnesses, set to fly in from abroad, caught=
 Young=E2=80=99s lawyers
off guard. In response, they asked Judge Henry to reopen discovery, but he =
refused. CNN, for its part, accused Young=E2=80=99s team of intimidating th=
e witnesses by raising the specter of liability for false statements and wa=
rning of potential bad press from other outlets. As CNN attorney Tobin put =
it, =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s irony in how they are offensively trying to us=
e the media.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;">For some reason, this trial continues to fly under =
the radar,
apart from=C2=A0 right-wing outlets that are reveling in the possibility of=
 CNN=E2=80=99s embarrassment. CNN, no doubt, hopes for a low-profile trial =
with an outcome as muted as Netflix=E2=80=99s victory in the <em>Our Father=
</em> privacy case. But with punitive damages on the table, <strong>Ron DeS=
antis</strong> appointees reshaping Florida=E2=80=99s appellate courts, Tru=
mp allies positioned at the federal level, and a legal climate growing less=
 hospitable to speech deemed harmful to the national interest, this case
may go places. Also, thanks to Florida=E2=80=99s tolerance of cameras in th=
e courtrooms, there=E2=80=99s a good chance it=E2=80=99ll be livestreamed.<=
/p></div>
